\subsection{Exploratory Data Analysis}
Exploratory analysis revealed several meaningful patterns in the data. At the 
time-series level, weekly sales volume exhibits significant annual seasonality, with 
a recurring peak in April each year that closely coincides with Easter. A systematic 
increase in sales in the two weeks leading up to Easter, followed by a rapid 
decline, was consistently observed across multiple years. An abnormal peak occurred in April 2020, determined to be due to stockpiling behavior at the beginning of the COVID-19 pandemic. However, this disturbance lacks cyclical regularity, and a COVID flag variable will be introduced during feature engineering to differentiate it.
\\
\\At the product level, the sales distribution has a highly right-skewed, 
long-tail structure, with a median weekly sales volume of 17 and a maximum value 
exceeding 1,300. This indicates variation in product size across the dataset. The seasonal patterns, holiday effects, COVID disturbances, and product sparsity revealed in the Data Understanding phase together form empirical basis for data preparation and feature engineering phases.
